ing Language grows out of the author’s experience of hearing loss in which misunderstandings have become a daily occurrence. Davidson maintains that verbal confusions are less an aberration in understanding than a component of new knowledge.Davidson discusses a range of sites, from captioning errors and Bad Lip Reads on YouTube, to the deaf artist Christine Sun Kim’s audiovisual installations, and a poetic reinterpretation of the Biblical Shibboleth responding to the atrocities of the Holocaust. Deafness becomes a guide in each chapter of Distressing Language, giving us a closer look at a range of artistic mediums and how artists are working with the axiom of “error” to produce novel subjecthoods and possibilities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication and the arts. 0aMiscommunication in art. 0aMiscommunication in literature. 0aPeople with disabilities and the arts. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAIDS/HIV.  aAlison O’Daniel.  aAudio.  aCaptions.  aCarolyn Lazard.  aCatherine Yass.  aChristian Marclay.  aChristine Sun Kim.  aCitizens United.  aComprehension.  aCrip.  aDeaf gain.  aDeafness.  aDisability.  aError.  aGeorges Canguilhem.  aJacques Ranciere.  aJena Osman.  aLanguage.  aLarry Eigner.  aLipreading.  aLiza Sylvestre.  aMalaprops.  aMishearing.  aMisspeaking.  aMistake.  aRedistribution.  aRobert Fitterman.  aShibboleth.  aThe Sound of Metal.  aTrump administration.  aaeolian harp.  aappropriation.  acerebral palsy.  acommunicational feedback.  acoronavirus.  acorporate subject.  acrip temporality.  ad/Deaf culture.  adisability studies.  adistributed voice.  aerror.  ainner speech.  alegal subject.  amodernism.  amondegreens.  anon-cochlear music.  apost-truth.  aslow poetics.  asoun